				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The NES generates its palette by generating a wave for each pixel, which NTSC televisions interpret as hue (from phase), luminance (from a DC offset), and saturation (from amplitude of the wave).
<br />
<br />As I understand it, the NES creates this wave by alternating between the two sets of grays.
<br />
<br />For example, to create the color $11, the nes outputs xxxxxxyyyyyy, where x is the gray at $01, and y is the gray at $d1. This makes a square wave.
<br />
<br />xxxxxxyyyyyy is color $1x, yxxxxxxyyyyy is $2x (or is it $cx?), yyxxxxxxyyyy being the next color after that, etc etc.
<br />
<br />Those grays aren't waves though, they're just plain flat voltages. However, by alternating between those two flat voltages, that's how the wave is created, and like I said, $0x is one peak, and $dx is the other peak.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />-Drag</div>
