					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">JohnJohn wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Now there is a third, even darker gray that's not visible when the default palette is turned on. Is this gray used anywhere?<br /><br />By the way, do you have any idea why they have two whites instead of white and another gray?</div>
<br />
<br />Check out <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=2113" class="postlink">this post</a> by Kevtris.  It explains how the hues of the NES are generated by cycling the voltage between the two extremes (colours x0 and xD).  Kev's doc was eye-opening, and explained a few things that I'd always suspected.
<br />
<br />Anyway, the designers of the NES/FC PPU had to step up the luminance and saturation <em>together</em> in only 6 steps (black, white, plus 4 intermediary levels for the hues) so they chose those x0 and xD levels for this purpose (even if it means two repeated whites.)</div>

