						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Specifically in the case of the NES, a PAL machine gives you an extra 70 scanlines' time to redraw the screen, which is nice.</div>
<br />Unless it's a PAL/M machine from Brazil, which is more like an NTSC machine because it uses a daughterboard to convert NTSC to PAL/M.
<br />
<br />The disadvantage of regular PAL is flicker. Lots of flicker. I can't see flicker at 60 Hz but I can see it at 50 Hz. The other disadvantage, in the case of the NES, is more visible artifacts at the top and bottom in certain mirroring modes.</div>

